    <edge source=" trial, the Parole Board hearings are the only chance to participate in the judicial process. Why are victims not permitted on the video conference, while staff, panels and inmates are?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Marco Mendicino&#10;Content: Madam Chair, as I've said now on a number of occasions, victims are able to participate in the hearings before the Parole Board. This is as a result of technology and innovations introduced by the Parole Board. Of course, those opportunities will continue to exist going forward.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Colin Carrie&#10;Content: Then, Madam Chair, why did the minister and this government tell Canadians and the House that victims of crime have the opportunity to participate in parole hearings by video conference, when in fact they do not?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Marco Mendicino&#10;Content: Madam Chair, as I've said, of course we are going to confirm the status of that particular request. In the meantime, as I've said on a number of occasions, victims are able to participate in these hearings. This is consistent with the fairness of those hearings and the due process we accord to them.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Colin Carrie&#10;Content: Madam Chair, it's been over a month" target="1. Adequate funding for indigenous police forces: According to Mr. Steven MacKinnon, the federal government should work with indigenous peoples, Quebec, and the provinces to establish appropriate funding for indigenous police forces. This is in response to the recommendation from the reports of the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which called for improved funding and support for indigenous law enforcement.&#10;2. Civilian ethics organizations for the RCMP: Another action highlighted by Mr. MacKinnon is the creation of civilian ethics organizations to oversee the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP). This recommendation also comes from the reports of the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which suggested increased accountability for the RCMP in their interactions with indigenous communities.&#10;3. Education on indigenous realities and cultures: Mr. MacKinnon emphasized the need for better education on indigenous realities and cultures for both police officers and the general population. This recommendation is also present in the reports of the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which called for increased awareness and understanding of indigenous peoples' histories and cultures to foster healthier relationships between indigenous and non-indigenous communities.&#10;4. Confidence restoration and reconciliation: Lastly, Mr. MacKinnon mentioned the importance of taking actions that will help restore confidence in law enforcement and achieve long-overdue reconciliation with indigenous peoples. This is consistent with the overall objective of the reports from the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which stressed the need for urgent action to address the systemic issues contributing to the ongoing violence against indigenous women and girls in Canada.">
