    <edge source=" how many parole hearings have been conducted under this digital format with victims since April 29?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Marco Mendicino (Minister of Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship)&#10;Content: Thank you, Madam Chair. I thank my honourable colleague for the question. I'm glad to hear that Minister Blair was able to provide information on the specific case he raises. With regard to his question, we're happy to provide it to him in due course.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Colin Carrie&#10;Content: Madame Chair, on April 29 the minister said, and I quote, Steps have been taken to make it possible for victims to participate in those parole hearings virtually by phone or video conference. If the change has been made, can the minister please tell us how many hearings victims have been able to participate in by video conference?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Marco Mendicino&#10;Content: Madam Chair, as I said, certainly we will confirm the number of hearings that may have occurred. With regard to the hearings under the Parole Board of Canada, we want to ensure that victims and others are able to participate in a fair and transparent manner.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Colin Carrie&#10;Content: Madame Chair, the website says, To protect" target="1. GBA+ analysis on COVID-19 relief programs: The transcript shows that the question was asked multiple times, but not directly addressed by Hon. Carla Qualtrough, the minister responsible. From the information provided, it appears that no GBA+ (Gender-based Analysis Plus) analyses were conducted specifically for the COVID-19 relief programs. The minister mentions that they took into account the needs of women and girls but does not explicitly confirm if a GBA+ analysis was carried out.&#10;2. Number of parole hearings with victims present in digital format: Mr. Colin Carrie asked this question twice, but it wasn't directly answered by Hon. Marco Mendicino, the minister responsible. The Parole Board of Canada has been conducting its hearings r