ed increased accountability for the RCMP in their interactions with indigenous communities.&#10;3. Education on indigenous realities and cultures: Mr. MacKinnon emphasized the need for better education on indigenous realities and cultures for both police officers and the general population. This recommendation is also present in the reports of the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which called for increased awareness and understanding of indigenous peoples' histories and cultures to foster healthier relationships between indigenous and non-indigenous communities.&#10;4. Confidence restoration and reconciliation: Lastly, Mr. MacKinnon mentioned the importance of taking actions that will help restore confidence in law enforcement and achieve long-overdue reconciliation with indigenous peoples. This is consistent with the overall objective of the reports from the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which stressed the need for urgent action to address the systemic issues contributing to the ongoing violence against indigenous women and girls in Canada.">
