    <edge source="1. Adequate funding for indigenous police forces: According to Mr. Steven MacKinnon, the federal government should work with indigenous peoples, Quebec, and the provinces to establish appropriate funding for indigenous police forces. This is in response to the recommendation from the reports of the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which called for improved funding and support for indigenous law enforcement.&#10;2. Civilian ethics organizations for the RCMP: Another action highlighted by Mr. MacKinnon is the creation of civilian ethics organizations to oversee the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP). This recommendation also comes from the reports of the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which suggested increased accountability for the RCMP in their interactions with indigenous communities.&#10;3. Education on indigenous realities and cultures: Mr. MacKinnon emphasized the need for better education on indigenous realities and cultures for both police officers and the general population. This recommendation is also present in the reports of the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which called for increased awareness and understanding of indigenous peoples' histories and cultures to foster healthier relationships between indigenous and non-indigenous communities.&#10;4. Confidence restoration and reconciliation: Lastly, Mr. MacKinnon mentioned the importance of taking actions that will help restore confidence in law enforcement and achieve long-overdue reconciliation with indigenous peoples. This is consistent with the overall objective of the reports from the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, which stressed the need for urgent action to address the systemic issues contributing to the ongoing violence against indigenous women and girls in Canada." target=" report and the report stemming from the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls contained dozens of recommendations. The federal government must work with indigenous peoples, Quebec and the provinces to establish adequate funding for indigenous police forces. Civilian ethics organizations should be created to oversee the RCMP. Police officers and the general population must be better educated on indigenous realities and cultures. Hundreds of pages must be written and actions taken to restore confidence in law enforcement so as to achieve the long-overdue reconciliation. Let's take action.&#10;Speaker: The Chair&#10;Content: I give the floor to Mr.MacKinnon.&#10;Speaker: Mr. Steven MacKinnon (Gatineau, Lib.)&#10;Content: Mr.Chair, on behalf of myself and my parliamentary colleagues, I want to congratulate students from our high school class of 2020. We know that, owing to the pandemic, graduation celebrations will be different this year, as students will be deprived of their prom, their graduation ceremony and, in some cases, their goodbyes to friends and teachers. I know how disappointed students from the high schools of duVersant, LeCarrefour, Nicolas-Gatineau, de l'rablire, Collge Saint-Alexandre,">
